Loading Data:¶

Data from Instagram (IG) posts are loaded for three companies used for the analysis: Offcorss, EPK and Polito:

In [4]:
# Companies included in the analysis:
company_names = ['offcorss', 'epk', 'polito']
In [5]:
# Function to get the text from the posts:
def get_post_text(value):
    if len(value['edges']) > 0:
        texto = value['edges'][0]['node']['text']
    else:
        texto = ''
    return texto
In [6]:
# Function to get the hashtags from the text in each post:
def get_hashtags(texto):
    hashtags = []
    texto = nltk.word_tokenize(texto)
    for i, word in enumerate(texto):
        if word=='#' and i<(len(texto)-1):
            hashtags.append(texto[i+1])
    return hashtags
In [ ]:
# Reading json files with Instagram posts for all companies:
company_posts_df = []
for company in company_names:
    files_list = glob.glob(f'/home/jovyan/work/DS4A/Project/Instagram/{company}/*.json')
    
    list_of_df = []
    for file in files_list:
        if 'comment' not in file:
            temp_df = pd.read_json(file).drop(columns='instaloader')
            list_of_df.append(temp_df)
    company_posts = pd.concat(list_of_df, axis=1).transpose()
    df_info = ['display_url', 'edge_media_preview_like', 'edge_media_to_caption', 'edge_media_to_comment', 'id', 'taken_at_timestamp']
    company_posts = company_posts.loc[:, df_info]
    company_posts['posts_company'] = company
    company_posts_df.append(company_posts)    
    
ig_posts = pd.concat(company_posts_df)
ig_posts = ig_posts.rename(columns={'display_url':'post_url',
                          'edge_media_preview_like':'post_likes_count',
                         'edge_media_to_caption':'post_text',
                         'edge_media_to_comment':'post_comments_count',
                         'id':'post_id',
                         'taken_at_timestamp':'post_date'})
ig_posts = ig_posts.reset_index(drop=True)
ig_posts = ig_posts.dropna(axis=0)

ig_posts['post_likes_count'] = ig_posts['post_likes_count'].apply(lambda x: x['count'])
ig_posts['post_comments_count'] = ig_posts['post_comments_count'].apply(lambda x: x['count'])
ig_posts['post_date'] = ig_posts['post_date'].apply(lambda x: datetime.fromtimestamp(x))

ig_posts['post_text'] = ig_posts['post_text'].apply(get_post_text)
ig_posts['post_hashtags'] = ig_posts['post_text'].apply(get_hashtags)
ig_posts['post_text'] = ig_posts['post_text'].apply(lambda x: x.split(' #')[0])

The Instagram posts from these three competitors are loaded into "ig_posts" dataframe which has this information:

Dataset: "ig_posts":

  • post_comments_count: Number of comments per post.
  • post_date: Date when the post was created.
  • post_hashtags: List of Hashtags included in each post.
  • post_id: ID of the post. Unique identifier.
  • post_likes_count: Number of likes per post.
  • post_text: Text in the post.
  • post_url: URL of the post.
  • posts_company: Company.

Non-Stopping Words:¶

Stopping words were removed from the text of the posts, so the most common words used in the posts can be analyzed for each company:

In [19]:
def remove_stopping_words(value):
    non_stopping_words = []
    for x in value:
        if x not in stopwords.words(['spanish', 'english']) and x.isalpha():
            non_stopping_words.append(x)
    return non_stopping_words

Hashtags Analysis:¶

Below we can find the top10 hashtags that are used in the posts by each company:

In [190]:
# Defining function to get and plot the top10 hashtags used in the posts:
def get_top10_hashtags(company, hashtag_column, company_column):
    hashtags_column = company[hashtag_column]
    hashtags_column = hashtags_column.apply(lambda x: ' '.join(x))
    
    vec = CountVectorizer()
    X = vec.fit_transform(hashtags_column)
    hashtags = pd.DataFrame(X.toarray(), columns=vec.get_feature_names())
    
    dic = {}
    for word in list(hashtags.columns):
        dic[word] = hashtags[word].sum()
    
    df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(dic, orient='index').rename(columns={0:'Hashtag'})    
    plot = df.sort_values(by='Hashtag', ascending=True).tail(10).plot(kind='barh', label='')    
    plt.title(f"Top 10 Hashtags from {str.upper(company[company_column].unique()[0])}")
    plt.show()
    
    return plot

ig_responses = pd.read_csv(r'instagram_responses.csv')

The "ig_responses" dataset contains the responses to each post for each company:

Dataset: "ig_responses":

  • rootPost_id: ID of the post which the response belongs to.
  • response_post_id: ID of the response.
  • brand_username: Company.
  • text: Response's text.
  • time: Datetime when the response was made.
  • likes: Response's likes count.
  • username: Username of the person making the response.
  • hashtags: List of hashtags used in the response.
  • text_nsw: Response's text containing non-stopping words.
  • text_lenght: Response's lenght.

from nltk.util import ngrams
from collections import Counter

# Defining function to get top n-grams:
def top_k_ngrams(word_tokens, n, k):    
    n_gram_list = list(ngrams(word_tokens, n))    
    n_gram_strings = [' '.join(each) for each in n_gram_list]
    n_gram_counter = Counter(n_gram_strings)
    most_common_k = n_gram_counter.most_common(k)
    print(most_common_k)

  • The plot above shows the average lenght of the responses to Instagram posts for each company grouped by month. OFFCORSS and EPK have similar responses' lengths along the year, while the responses to POLITO's posts tend to be longer especially along May-August (where the number of posts from this company increases as showed in the analysis above).
